    =COUNTIFS($G$14:$G$185, Gr, $J$14:$J$185, "Open")

We will write this into each cell I14 through I185, preserving any existing formatting (openpyxl keeps cell style unless we replace the cell). After saving, we will call `recalculate` to evaluate formulas, reload the workbook with `data_only=True`, and print a few sample results to verify they are not None. Finally we will save the workbook to the output directory and submit the output file path.
Code:
```repl
import os
import openpyxl
from openpyxl.utils import get_column_letter

# Paths
input_path = input_spreadsheet  # provided variable
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, os.path.basename(input_path))

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = openpyxl.load_workbook(input_path)
ws = wb[wb.sheetnames[0]]  # assume first sheet is target

# Identify merged ranges that include column I (9) and rows 14-185
to_unmerge = []
for mr in ws.merged_cells.ranges:
    min_col, min_row, max_col, max_row = mr.bounds
    if min_col <= 9 <= max_col and max_row >= 14 and min_row <= 185:
        to_unmerge.append(mr)

# Unmerge them
for mr in to_unmerge:
    ws.unmerge_cells(str(mr))

# Write formula into column I for rows 14 to 185 (or up to ws.max_row if larger)
start_row = 14
end_row = max(ws.max_row, 185)  # ensure we cover at least 185
for r in range(start_row, end_row + 1):
    # Build formula string
    formula = f'=COUNTIFS($G$14:$G$185, G{r}, $J$14:$J$185, "Open")'
    ws.cell(row=r, column=9).value = formula  # column I = 9

# Save workbook to output path
wb.save(output_path)

# Recalculate formulas (async)
calc_result = await recalculate(output_path)
print("Recalculate result:", calc_result)

# Reload with data_only to verify computed values
wb2 = openpyxl.load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
ws2 = wb2[wb2.sheetnames[0]]

# Print sample I values after recalculation
print("Sample I column values after recalculation:")
for r in [14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 54, 144, 185]:
    val = ws2.cell(row=r, column=9).value
    print(f"Row {r}: I = {val}")

# Ensure the output file exists
print("Output file written to:", output_path)
```
